FIG. S1: Image analysis pipeline used to automatically track planar cell position and orientation as well as flagellar shapes in high-speed movies of swimming Chlamydomonas cells. 0. A typical movie frame 1. Rotated template images used for a cross-correlation analysis to estimate cell position and orientation in a movie frame. 2. The cell body outline was tracked by detecting intensity maxima (green) of line scans along rays (shown in blue), which emanate from the putative cell body center. From the cell body outline, we obtain refined estimates for cell position and orientation. 3. The position of the flagellar base was then determined using a fan of line-scans (along the blue lines), followed by a line-scan (green) in a direction perpendicular to the maximal intensity direction (red). 4. Finally, flagellar shapes were tracked in a successive manner using similar combinations of line-scans as in step 3.

