FIG. S9: Theoretical coupling functions for the case of a pivoting flagellar base. A. A pivoting motion of the flagellar base changes the hydrodynamic friction force associated with flagellar beating and thereby speeds up or slows down the flagellar beat cycle in our theory. This effect is quantified by a coupling function , see equation S18. B. Hydrodynamic friction associated with pivoting of the flagellar base (and the attached flagella) is characterized by a friction coefficient , see equation S20. This friction coefficient is maximal when the two flagella extend maximally from the cell body during their effective stroke. C. The beat of the left flagellum causes pivoting of the flagellar base. This effect is quantified by a coupling function  , see eqn. S20.

